# Deploying to Databricks Apps

This project deploys as a Databricks Asset Bundle. The bundle definition lives
in `databricks.yml`; the app's runtime manifest is `app.yaml`.

## One-time setup

1. Install the Databricks CLI v0.220+ and authenticate against your workspace.
2. Set the workspace URL: `databricks bundle validate -t dev -p <profile>`.
3. (In CI) configure Workload Identity Federation — see `.github/workflows/deploy.yml`.

## Deploy from your machine

```bash
just bundle-validate          # dry-run, catches schema errors early
just deploy                   # bundle deploy + bundle run
```

## What gets uploaded

The bundle uploads:

- The compiled binary at `target/release/{{ project_name | kebab_case }}-server`
- The `app.yaml` manifest
- Any static frontend assets in `frontend/dist/` (if `with_frontend=true`)

It does **not** upload `target/debug`, `node_modules`, or local stack data.

## Env vars on Databricks

Databricks Apps automatically injects:

- `DATABRICKS_HOST` — the workspace URL (e.g. `https://your-ws.cloud.databricks.com`)
- `DATABRICKS_APP_URL` — the app's public URL
- `DATABRICKS_APP_PORT` — the port the app should listen on
- `X-Forwarded-Access-Token` (per-request) — the calling user's OBO token
- `X-Forwarded-User` / `X-Forwarded-Email` (per-request) — identity headers

Anything else you need (MLflow URIs, custom config) goes in `app.yaml`'s `env:`
block, set per-environment in `databricks.yml`.

## Smoke test

After `databricks bundle run {{ project_name | snake_case }}`, the app URL is
printed. The trestle template wires a `/healthz` endpoint; CI's
`deploy.yml` job hits it as a smoke test.

## Common pitfalls

- **MLflow experiment IDs differ** between local and Databricks. Use experiment
  *names*, not IDs.
- **First deploy after a proto change**: run `just regen` first, then deploy.
- **403 from MLflow on Databricks**: the OBO token doesn't have MLflow access
  in this workspace — grant it in workspace settings.
